          <note>Due to his profiency in vyākaraṇa, he was called Pratyagra-Patañjali, i.e. 'The Modern Patañjali', by his contemporaries (The Indian Antiquary vol. 43, pg. 129 T. S. Kuppuswami Sastri).</note>
          <note>Raghavan in his intro to Śāhendravilāsa (pg. 41) suggests a sojourn at Madura for Rāmabhadra Dīkṣita on account of the mention of Madura as the venue of the enactment of of his Śṛṅgāratilakabhāṇa. See also Thiruvengadathan pg. 11</note>
          <note>Ṛgvedin, Kauṇḍinyagotra (Raghavan intro to Śāhendravilāsa pg. 40)</note>
          <note>Recipient of 4 shares of Thiruvisanallur, as he was a master in 4 śāstras: alaṁkāra, vyākaraṇa, mīmāṁsā, and vedānta (see Thiruvengadathan and Raghavan)</note>
          <note>He was hailed as pratyagrapatañjali, dvitīyaprācetasa, dvitīyavālmīki, sāhiytaratnakośa, śabdabrahmasvarūpī, and rāmabhaktyabdhi by his contemporaries (see Thiruvengadathan pg. 13)</note>
